title: Before You Surrender Your Pet to a Rescue/Shelter
description:
QR Code Link to This Post


If you are considering giving your pet up for adoption to a rescue/shelter, don't select the one closest to your home because it is convenient. Make sure the organization has a no-kill philosophy. Read as many reviews of various organizations as possible and check their websites. Some rescues/shelters don't have websites, I consider that a red flag. Some rescues/shelters are so particular about to whom they adopt out their animals, it's easier to adopt a child. Look at the fees the organization is charging for their pets. Many of them charge almost as much as a reputable breeder which makes it difficult for them to adopt out your pet, so the animal may not live in a permanent home for months. Try to get a referral from people you know who have had experiences with various rescues/shelters.

 Dwight and Darlene Uhter started Paws Critter Crossing (PCC), located in Cook County, Illinois, in 1950 with just a handful of animals. As the years passed by they took more and more animals each year. Some were bought and some were brought and now the refuge is a safe haven for almost 100 permanent residents. The permanent residence at PCC consists of animals that were unwanted or neglected by agencies/people and indigenous and non-indigenous wild animals that have been captive breed. The Uhters enjoyed caring for their animals so much, they decided to start helping wildlife as well. So, it was then that Paws Critter Crossing became a two-fold operation.

 In 1999 PCC was incorporated as a non-profit organization striving to keep the refuge open for community outreach and education and to rehabilitate and safely release orphaned, injured and displaced wildlife. All the animals that are at or brought to PCC are cared for and provided with veterinary treatment if needed. The rehabilitated wildlife animals are treated and released unless they are too weak to survive.

* PLEASE HELP THE ANIMALS * Paws Critter Crossing 
 Dwight and Darlene Uhter started Paws Critter Crossing (PCC), located in Cook County, Illinois, in 1950 with just a handful of animals. As the years passed by they took more and more animals each year. Some were bought and some were brought and now the refuge is a safe haven for almost 100 permanent residents. The permanent residence at PCC consists of animals that were unwanted or neglected by agencies/people and indigenous and non-indigenous wild animals that have been captive breed. The Uhters enjoyed caring for their animals so much, they decided to start helping wildlife as well. So, it was then that Paws Critter Crossing became a two-fold operation.

 In 1999 PCC was incorporated as a non-profit organization striving to keep the refuge open for community outreach and education and to rehabilitate and safely release orphaned, injured and displaced wildlife. All the animals that are at or brought to PCC are cared for and provided with veterinary treatment if needed. The rehabilitated wildlife animals are treated and released unless they are too weak to survive.

 Our work at PCC is provided entirely by volunteers and funded solely by public donations. We receive no financial assistance from any government organization or agency. She loves to obey and please, so she has a great foundation for learning. When Maggie arrived at IDR+, there was some bone exposed on her tail, most likely from having “happy tail.” We have it wrapped so that she will not further injure her tail. Once it fully heals, she should have no further issues. She could also stand to gain some healthy weight, and will probably round out at about 100-110 pounds.
